u} \equiv  rac{p}{a^{\lambda}} \Leftrightarrow \exists  eta \in  bN _I 	ext{ such that } ma^{ eta + \lambda }= p a^{ eta + 
u } 	ext{ in } A.\] From now on, we abuse notation and denote a class by any of its representative $ rac{m}{a^{
u}}$ if no confusion is likely. $ ullet$ The addition law is given by $ rac{m}{a^{
u}}+  rac{p}{a^{ eta}}=  rac{m a^{ eta } + p a^{
u}}{a^{ eta + 
u}}$. $ ullet$ The multiplication law is given by $ rac{m}{a^{
u}}	imes  rac{p}{a^{ eta}} =  rac{ mp}{a^{
u +  eta }}$. $ ullet$ The additive neutral element is $ rac{0}{1}$ and the multiplicative neutral element is $ rac{1}{1}$.  egin{flushleft} From now on, we also use the notation $A[ rac{M}{a}]$ to denote $A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]$. We have a canonical morphism of rings $A 	o A[ rac{M}{a}]$ given by $a \mapsto  rac{a}{1}$. \end{flushleft} \xdepr The element $ rac{a}{1}$ of $ A[ rac{M}{a}]$ will be denoted by $a$ if no confusion is likely.  act[{\cite{Ma23d}}] \label{remdilaring}  egin{enumerate} \item Let $\{N_i\}_{i \in I}$ be ideals in $A$ such that $ N_i +(a_i) = L_i$ for all $i \in I$. Then we have identifications of $A$-algebras $A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]= A[ ig\{  rac{N_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]= A[ ig\{  rac{L_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}].$ \item Dilatations of rings generalize entirely localizations of rings. Indeed, let $A$ be a ring and let $S$ be a multiplicative subset of $A$. Then $S^{-1} A = A[ ig\{  rac{A}{s} ig\}_{s \in S}]$. \item Any sub-$A$-algebra of a localization $S^{-1} A$ for a subset $S \subset A$ can be obtained as a multi-centered dilatation. \item Note that we did not used substraction to define dilatations of rings. In fact Definition ef{generaldila} makes sense for arbitrary unital commutative semirings, cf. \cite[§2]{Ma23d} or more generally for categories (e.g. monoids) cf. \cite{Ma23c}. \end{enumerate} \xfact This construction enjoys the following properties, cf. \cite[§2]{Ma23d}. If $\#I=1$, most results appear in \cite[\href{https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/052P}{Tag 052P}]{stacks-project}. \prop[{\cite{Ma23d}}] The following assertions hold.  egin{enumerate} \item As $A$-algebra, $A[ rac{M}{a}]$ is generated by $ ig\{  rac{L_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}$. Since $L_i=M_i+(a_i)$, this implies that $A[ rac{M}{a}]$ is generated by $ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}$. \item If $A$ is a domain and $a_i 
e 0$ for all $i$, then $A[ rac{M}{a}]$ is a domain. \item If $A$ is reduced, then $A[ rac{M}{a}]$ is reduced. \item The following assertions are equivalent. egin{enumerate} \item There exists $
u \in  bN_I$ such that $a^
u =0$ in $A$. \item The ring $A[ rac{M}{a}]$ equals to the zero ring.\end{enumerate} \item Let $
u $ be in $\mathbb{N} _I$. The image of $a ^
u$ in $A[ rac{M}{a}]$ is a non-zero-divisor. \item Let $f:A 	o B$ be a morphism of rings. Let $\{[N_i,b_i]\}_{i \in I}$ be centers of $B$ such that $f(M_i) \subset N_i$ and $f(a_i)=b_i$ for all $i\in I$. Then we have a canonical morphism of $A$-algebras  egin{center} $\phi: A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}] 	o B[ ig\{  rac{N_i}{b_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]$ .\end{center} \item Let $c$ be a non-zero-divisor element in $A$. Then $ rac{c}{1}$ is a non-zero-divisor in $A[ rac{M}{a}]$. \item Let $K \subset I$ put $J = I \setminus K$. Then we have a canonical morphism of $A$-algebras  egin{center} $ \varphi :A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in K}] \longrightarrow A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}] . $ \end{center} Moreover  egin{enumerate} \item if $M_i\subset (a_i)$ for all $i \in J$, then $\varphi$ is surjective, and \item if $a_i$ is a non-zero-divisor in $A$ for all $i \in J$, then $\varphi$ is injective. \end{enumerate} \item Let $K \subset I$. Then we have a canonical isomorphism of $ A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in K}]$-algebras  egin{center} $A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}] = A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in K}] [ ig\{  rac{A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}] rac{M_j}{1}}{ rac{a_j}{1}} ig\}_{j \in I \setminus K}], $ \end{center} where ${A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}] rac{M_j}{1}}$ is the ideal of $A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]$ generated by $ rac{M_j}{1} \subset A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]$. \item Assume that $a_i=a_j=:b$ for all $i,j \in I$, then  egin{center}$A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]= A[ rac{\sum _{i\in I}M_i }{b}]$ \end{center} \item Let $
u \in  bN _I$. We have $L^
u A[ rac{M}{a}] = a^
u A[ rac{M}{a}]$. \item (Universal property) If $\chi : A 	o B$ is a morphism of rings such that $\chi (a_i) $ is a non-zero-divisor and generates $\chi (L_i) B$ for all $i\in I$, then there exists a unique morphism $\chi '$ of $A$-algebras $A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}] 	o B$. The morphism $\chi'$ sends $ rac{l}{a^
u} $ ($
u \in  bN _I , l \in L^
u$) to the unique element $b \in B $ such that $\chi ( a^
u) b = \chi (l)$. \item Assume that $I = \{1 , \ldots , k \}$ is finite. Then we have a canonical identification of $A$-algebras  egin{center}$A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]= A[ rac{\sum _{i \in I} ( M_i \cdot \prod _{j \in I \setminus {\{i\}}} a_j )}{a_1 \cdots a_k}] .$\end{center} \item Write $I= \colim _{J\subset I } J $ as a filtered colimit of sets. We have a canonical identification of $A$-algebras  egin{center} $A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}] = \colim _{J \subset I} A[ ig\{  rac{M_j}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in J}] $.\end{center} \item Let $f:A 	o B$ be an $A$-algebra. Put $N_i=f(M_i) B$ and $b_i = f(a_i)$ for $i \in I$. Then $B [ ig\{  rac{N_i}{b_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]$ is the quotient of $B \otimes _{A} A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]$ by the ideal $T_b$ of elements annihilated by some element in $b^{\mathbb{N} _I }:= \{b^
u | 
u \in  bN _I \}$. If moreover $f:A	o B$ is flat, then $T_b=0$ and we have a canonical isomorphism  egin{center} $B [\{  rac{N_i}{b_i} \}_{i \in I }] = B \otimes _A A[\{ rac{M_i}{a_i}\}_{i\in I}].$\end{center} \item Let $f:R	o A$ be a morphism of rings and let $\{r_i\}_{i\in I}\subset R$. Let $R'=R[  ig\{  rac{R}{r_i}  ig\}_{i\in I}]$; this is a localization of $R$ and hence $R	o R'$ is a flat morphism. Let $A'=A\otimes_R R'$, $M_i'=M_i\otimes_RR'\subset A'$. Then, if $a_i:=f(r_i)$, the dilatation $ A[ ig\{  rac{M_i}{a_i} ig\}_{i \in I}]$ is isomorphic to the $A$-subalgebra of $A'=A \otimes _R R'$ generated by $\{M_i \otimes r_i^{-1} \}_{i\in I}$ and $A$. \end{enumerate} \xprop We finish with an important description of dilatations in a particular case, cf. \cite[Proposition 5.5]{Ma23d} and \cite[\href{https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/0BIQ}{Tag 0BIQ}]{stacks-project}. \prop \label{regupoly}Let $A$ be a ring. Let $a , g_1 , \ldots , g_n$ be a $H_1$-regular sequence in $A$ (cf. \cite[\href{https://stacks.math.columbia.edu/tag/062E}{Tag 062E}]{stacks-project} for $H_1$-regularity). Let $d_1 , \ldots , d_n$ be positive integers. The dilatation algebra identifies with a quotient of a polynomial algebra as follows  egin{center} $A[ rac{(g_1)}{a^{d_1}}, \ldots ,  rac{(g_n)}{a^{d_n}}]=A[x_1 , \ldots , x_n] / (g_1 -a^{d_1} x_1, \ldots , g_n -a^{d_n} x_n )$. \end{center} \xprop

